    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-09T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-09T13:00:00-05:00" n="292"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/8961</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Diplomatic Liaison Officer with the Supreme War
                        Council</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FAH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Frazier</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-09T18:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 9, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 10, 4.13 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>146. Prime Ministers are now drafting a note to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName> regarding his reply to German peace
                    proposals. The tenor of this reply will be (that the?) evacuation of occupied
                    territories is not sufficient guarantee. Marshal <persName corresp="#p_FF1"
                        >Foch</persName> stated before the Prime Ministers that the terms of
                    armistice shift from day to day according to the military situation; in view of
                    the great victory by the British and French troops north of Saint-Quentin
                    yesterday the terms of an armistice tomorrow will be different from those of
                    today. I hope to obtain a copy of this joint note at 6 o’clock tonight and will
                    telegraph it as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FAH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Frazier</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
